sec.p:
On the basis of matrix factorization (MF), a common rating model, our objective is to learn a rating prediction model $f_{\theta}\left(x_{u, i}\right)=\operatorname{Pr}\left(y_{u, i}=1 \mid x_{u, i}\right)=\hat{y}_{u, i} \in<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref0">[0], <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref1">[1]$. With full observability, the model would minimize the ideal risk,
\begin{equation*}
\mathcal{L}_{\text {ideal }}(\theta)=\frac{1}{|\mathcal{D}|} \sum_{(u, i) \in \mathcal{D}} \ell\left(\hat{y}_{u, i}, y_{u, i}\right)
\end{equation*}

Ideal loss, however, is intractable because most entries are missing and selection is typically MNAR, turning the goal to minimizes prediction inaccuracy over labeled data, $\mathcal{O}$, via a naive estimator,
\begin{equation*}
\mathcal{L}_{\text {naive }}=\frac{1}{|\mathcal{O}|} \sum_{(u, i) \in \mathcal{O}} \ell\left(\hat{y}_{u, i}, y_{u, i}\right)
\end{equation*}

disp-formula.tex-math:
\begin{equation*}
\operatorname{MAE}_{u}=\frac{1}{\left|\mathcal{O}_{u}\right|} \sum_{i \in \mathcal{O}_{u}}\left|y_{u, i}-f_{\theta}\left(x_{u, i}\right)\right| \in<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref0">[0], <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref1">[1]
\end{equation*}

sec.p:
2) Normalized rating distribution entropy. Let $n_{u, y}$ be the count of observed labels $y \in\{0,1\}$ for user $u_{r}$, and $q_{u}(y)=\frac{n_{u, y}}{n_{u, 0}+n_{u, 1}}$. Define
\begin{equation*}
\widetilde{H}_{u}=-\sum_{y=0}^{1} q_{u}(y) \log q_{u}(y), \quad H_{u}=\frac{\widetilde{H}_{u}}{\log 2} \in<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref0">[0], <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref1">[1]
\end{equation*}

3) Labeled rating coverage. To capture adequacy of supervision and mitigate the variance of label-only signals, we use
\begin{equation*}
C_{u}=\frac{\left|\mathcal{O}_{u}\right|}{M} \in<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref0">[0], <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref1">[1],
\end{equation*}

Aggregating to a probability and forming the pivot set. We form a convex score that decreases with "pivot-likeness":
\begin{equation*}
s_{u}=-\alpha_{1} \cdot \operatorname{MAE}_{u}+\alpha_{2} \cdot H_{u}+\alpha_{3} \cdot C_{u}, \quad \alpha_{j} \geq 0, \sum_{j=1}^{3} \alpha_{j}=1,
\end{equation*}

so $s_{u} \in[-1,0]$ and we map it to a probability by normalizing the sigmoid:
\begin{equation*}
\pi_{u}=\frac{\sigma\left(s_{u}\right)}{\sigma(0)-\sigma(-1)} \in<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref0">[0], <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref1">[1]
\end{equation*}

Rating Distribution Feature Extraction. For each user $u$,collect predicted probabilities over all items (observed and unobserved): $\hat{\mathbf{y}}_{u}=\left\{\hat{y}_{u 1}, \ldots, \hat{y}_{u M}\right\}$. We map $\hat{\mathbf{y}}_{u}$ to a $K$ dimensional soft CDF feature $\mathbf{g}_{u} \in \mathbb{R}^{K}$:
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
t_{k}=\frac{k}{K}, \quad \mathbf{g}_{u} & =\left[f^{(1)}\left(\hat{\mathbf{y}}_{u}\right), \ldots, f^{(K)}\left(\hat{\mathbf{y}}_{u}\right)\right], \\
f^{(k)}\left(\hat{\mathbf{y}}_{u}\right) & =\frac{1}{M} \sum_{i=1}^{M} \sigma\left(\tau\left(t_{k}-\hat{y}_{u, i}\right)\right), \quad k=1, \ldots, K.
\end{aligned}
\end{equation*}

Semi-Supervised Calibration Loss. For a non-pivot user $u \in \mathcal{P}_{-}$, measure distributional similarity to each pivot $v \in \mathcal{P}_{+}$with a distance $\delta\left(\mathbf{g}_{u}, \mathbf{g}_{v}\right)$ (where we use squared $\ell_{2}$-norm by default, though other metrics are possible). Define a soft neighborhood over pivots:
\begin{equation*}
w_{u \rightarrow v}=\frac{\exp \left(1 / \delta\left(\mathbf{g}_{u}, \mathbf{g}_{v}\right)\right)}{\sum_{v^{\prime} \in \mathcal{P}_{+}} \exp \left(1 / \delta\left(\mathbf{g}_{u}, \mathbf{g}_{v^{\prime}}\right)\right)},
\end{equation*}

and the semi-supervised RDC loss aggregates over non-pivots:
\begin{equation*}
\mathcal{L}_{\text{semi}}^{u}=\frac{1}{\left|\mathcal{P}_{+}\right|} \sum_{v \in \mathcal{P}_{+}} w_{u \rightarrow v} \delta\left(\mathbf{g}_{u}, \mathbf{g}_{v}\right)
\end{equation*}

and the semi-supervised RDC loss aggregates over non-pivots:
\begin{equation*}
\mathcal{L}_{\text {semi-cal }}(\theta)=\frac{1}{\left|\mathcal{P}_{-}\right|} \sum_{u \in \mathcal{P}_{-}} \mathcal{L}_{\text {semi }}^{u}
\end{equation*}

Overall, We optimize a calibration-augmented objective that combines the standard supervised loss on observed pairs with the semi-supervised calibration term. We consider cross entropy error on observed pairs as the base loss:
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
& \mathcal{L}_{\text {base }}(\theta)= \\
& -\frac{1}{\left|\mathcal{O}_{u}\right|} \sum_{(u, i) \in \mathcal{O}_{u}}\left[y_{u, i} \log \hat{y}_{u, i}+\left(1-y_{u, i}\right) \log \left(1-\hat{y}_{u, i}\right)\right] \\
& +\lambda \cdot \operatorname{Reg}(\theta)
\end{aligned}
\end{equation*}

where $\operatorname{Reg}(\theta)$ refers to a regularization term, and $\lambda>0$ is a hyperparameter controlling regularization. Then the overall optimization loss is
\begin{equation*}
\mathcal{L}_{\text {SemiSL-RDC }}=\mathcal{L}_{\text {base }}+\mu \mathcal{L}_{\text {semi-cal }},
\end{equation*}
